<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="109" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[113,1089,1234,1579]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1127,222,566]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="109" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,243,1234,1258]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Comments.</emphasis>
The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Seidlitz" authorityYear="1899" box="[360,497,1234,1258]" class="Insecta" family="Oedemeridae" genus="Dolichopyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[360,497,1234,1258]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Dolichopyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was formerly distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. Schmidt" authorityYear="1884" box="[849,935,1234,1258]" class="Insecta" family="Oedemeridae" genus="Chitona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[849,935,1234,1258]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Chitona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because of the long pygidium, reniform eyes and emarginate last visible sternite. In my revision of the oedemerid genera (
<bibRefCitation author="SVIHLA V." box="[269,407,1292,1322]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" pagination="141 - 238" refId="ref6980" refString="SVIHLA V. 1986: Revision of the generic classification of the Old World Oedemeridae (Coleoptera). Sbornik Narodniho Muzea v Praze, Rada B 41: 141 - 238." type="journal article" year="1986">ŠVIHLA 1986</bibRefCitation>
), I found these characters insufficient to justify the existence of two separate genera, so that I classified 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Seidlitz" authorityYear="1899" box="[533,671,1330,1354]" class="Insecta" family="Oedemeridae" genus="Dolichopyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[533,671,1330,1354]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Dolichopyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a subgenus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. Schmidt" authorityYear="1884" box="[856,942,1330,1354]" class="Insecta" family="Oedemeridae" genus="Chitona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[856,942,1330,1354]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Chitona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Over time as more species of both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. Schmidt" authorityYear="1884" box="[337,423,1362,1386]" class="Insecta" family="Oedemeridae" genus="Chitona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[337,423,1362,1386]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Chitona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Seidlitz" authorityYear="1899" box="[473,611,1362,1386]" class="Insecta" family="Oedemeridae" genus="Dolichopyga" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[473,611,1362,1386]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Dolichopyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were examined and revisions of other genera of the family were completed, it became evident that the shape of the eyes can be intermediate, e. g. in 
<taxonomicName authority="Pic, 1913" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1913" box="[231,503,1426,1450]" class="Insecta" family="Oedemeridae" genus="Chitona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="innotaticollis">
<emphasis box="[231,402,1426,1450]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">C. innotaticollis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="PIC M." box="[406,503,1426,1450]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" pagination="169 - 171" refId="ref6708" refString="PIC M. 1913: Notes diverses, descriptions et diagnoses (Suite). L'Echange, Revue Linneene 29: 169 - 171." type="journal article" year="1913">Pic,1913</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Reitter, 1889" authorityName="Reitter" authorityYear="1889" box="[556,860,1426,1450]" class="Insecta" family="Oedemeridae" genus="Chitona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ganglbaueri">
<emphasis box="[556,716,1426,1450]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">C. ganglbaueri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="REITTER E." box="[721,860,1426,1450]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" pagination="17 - 44" refId="ref6733" refString="REITTER E. 1889: Neue Coleopteren aus Europa, den angrenzenden Landern und Sibirien, mit Bemerkungen uber bekannte Arten. Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift 1889: 17 - 44." type="journal article" year="1889">Reitter, 1889</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, in which the eyes are only very slightly emarginate. It also seems that the shape of the eyes depends on the more or less rostrate head in the species formerly classified in the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. Schmidt" authorityYear="1884" box="[829,915,1490,1514]" class="Insecta" family="Oedemeridae" genus="Chitona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">
<emphasis box="[829,915,1490,1514]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Chitona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[921,977,1491,1514]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
Thus only the shape of the last abdominal segment remained as a distinguishing character. In comparison with other genera, e. g. 
<taxonomicName authority="Dejean, 1834" authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1834" box="[398,646,1554,1578]" class="Insecta" family="Oedemeridae" genus="Nacerdes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[398,498,1554,1578]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Nacerdes</emphasis>
Dejean, 1834
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Seidlitz, 1899" authorityName="Seidlitz" authorityYear="1899" box="[655,926,1554,1578]" class="Insecta" family="Oedemeridae" genus="Alloxantha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[655,772,1554,1578]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Alloxantha</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="SEIDLITZ G. C. M. VON" box="[777,926,1554,1578]" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" pagination="681 - 968" refId="ref6867" refString="SEIDLITZ G. C. M. VON 1899: Oedemeridae. Pp. 681 - 968. In: ERICHSON W. F., SCHAUM H. R., KRAATZ G., KIESENWETTER E. A. H. VON, WEISE J., REITTER E. &amp; SEIDLITZ G. C. M. VON (eds.): Naturgeschichte der Insekten Deutschlands. Erste Abtheilung Coleoptera. Funfter Band. Zweite Halfte. Nicolai, Berlin, 968 pp." type="book chapter" year="1899">Seidlitz, 1899</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Olivier, 1789" authorityName="Olivier" authorityYear="1789" class="Insecta" family="Oedemeridae" genus="Oedemera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="109" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[978,1089,1554,1578]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="108">Oedemera</emphasis>
Olivier, 1789
</taxonomicName>
, the above mentioned characters do not justify the existence of two distinct genera. Nevertheless, they can be used to define species groups.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1127,222,566]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">
Based on available material, the Western Mediterranean species seem to belong to only one group, which is a sister group of all Eastern Mediterranean species. This group is characterized by a narrowly emarginate apex of the last sternite and tendency to create rostrate head. Unfortunately, I could not examine all the known species occurring in the western part of the Mediterranean. The material of North African species is very limited and some 
<typeStatus box="[988,1044,414,438]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">types</typeStatus>
are lost or not available. That is why the whole genus is not revised in this paper. The groups of Eastern Mediterranean species are defined below.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1127,222,566]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,277,509,533]" pageId="2" pageNumber="109">Bionomics.</emphasis>
At least some but possibly all species occurring in eastern Mediterranean prefer saline biotopes, where their larvae develop in stems and roots of flowers.
</paragraph>
